    <item>
      <title>LIGO O4: multi-messenger</title>
      <link>https://ChenLi2049.github.io/posts/20230514-ligo-o4-multi-messenger/</link>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;LIGO is back on track with Observing Run 4 (O4)&lt;sup id=&#34;fnref:1&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fn:1&#34; class=&#34;footnote-ref&#34; role=&#34;doc-noteref&#34;&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;. And I got this idea:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Active Galactic Nucleus (AGN) is considered as a Gravitational Wave (GW) candidate that can be detected by LIGO-Virgo-Kagra&lt;sup id=&#34;fnref:2&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fn:2&#34; class=&#34;footnote-ref&#34; role=&#34;doc-noteref&#34;&gt;2&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;. And IceCube recently proposed a method to combine neutrino detection with radio detection in the observation of AGN&lt;sup id=&#34;fnref:3&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fn:3&#34; class=&#34;footnote-ref&#34; role=&#34;doc-noteref&#34;&gt;3&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;. So maybe these three messengers (GW, neutrino, radio) can work together to observe AGN. And maybe we should write a program that can synchronize these observations.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s exciting that we can make use of basically all the messengers that we know of. Except cosmic rays, but galactic cosmic rays mostly can&amp;rsquo;t reach earth anyway (because of their charge). However, their are few things we should consider:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;We don&amp;rsquo;t observe many GWs&lt;sup id=&#34;fnref:4&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fn:4&#34; class=&#34;footnote-ref&#34; role=&#34;doc-noteref&#34;&gt;4&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;, so we can just do it by hand.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A radio telescope can turn around, so it&amp;rsquo;s kind of urgent to focus on the target. But based on the way IceCube works, there&amp;rsquo;s no rush. IceCube, the basic part of which is a $1 \space \mathrm{km}^3$ ice cube, can&amp;rsquo;t turn around. LIGO can&amp;rsquo;t turn around either.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;footnotes&#34; role=&#34;doc-endnotes&#34;&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li id=&#34;fn:1&#34;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;See &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.ligo.org/news/index.php#ER15&#34;&gt;their news website&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.ligo.org/news/images/ER15-newsitem.pdf&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Gravitational wave detectors prepare for next observing run&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;#160;&lt;a href=&#34;#fnref:1&#34; class=&#34;footnote-backref&#34; role=&#34;doc-backlink&#34;&gt;&amp;#x21a9;&amp;#xfe0e;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li id=&#34;fn:2&#34;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;See &lt;a href=&#34;https://arxiv.org/abs/2304.10567&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Optical Emission Model for Binary Black Hole Merger Remnants Travelling through Discs of Active Galactic Nucleus&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. I later found out Virgo is delayed, see &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.virgo-gw.eu/news/virgo-postpones-entry-into-o4-observing-run/&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Virgo postpones entry into O4 observing run&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;#160;&lt;a href=&#34;#fnref:2&#34; class=&#34;footnote-backref&#34; role=&#34;doc-backlink&#34;&gt;&amp;#x21a9;&amp;#xfe0e;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li id=&#34;fn:3&#34;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;See &lt;a href=&#34;https://arxiv.org/abs/2304.12675&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Search for correlations of high-energy neutrinos detected in IceCube with radio-bright AGN and gamma-ray emission from blazars&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;#160;&lt;a href=&#34;#fnref:3&#34; class=&#34;footnote-backref&#34; role=&#34;doc-backlink&#34;&gt;&amp;#x21a9;&amp;#xfe0e;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li id=&#34;fn:4&#34;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;See &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.ligo.org/detections.php&#34;&gt;Detection of gravitational waves&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;#160;&lt;a href=&#34;#fnref:4&#34; class=&#34;footnote-backref&#34; role=&#34;doc-backlink&#34;&gt;&amp;#x21a9;&amp;#xfe0e;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
